english:
  title: Preface to the Filial Piety Ceremony of Cao Daxu, Doctor of the Hongmun Academy
  author: Kang Hui-maeng
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When parents give birth to a child cradled in swaddling clothes, they stroke its forehead and say, "Will you grow strong and fulfill our hopes?" When the child is older and sent to a teacher, they touch its back and ask, "Will you master your studies and honor our family name?" Day and night they make these wishes in their hearts and offer prayers to heaven. When someone praises the child once, the parents forget to eat from joy. When someone criticizes the child once, anxiety weighs upon their chests. This does not come from external causes—it is the truth of heaven's nature, without even a hair's breadth of falsity mixed within.

    Children depend upon their parents as if dwelling in an impregnable fortress. They fear no harm; thunder may crack above their heads without terror, fire and flood may surge before them without concern. Strange visions may suddenly chase them, yet dissolving into their parents' embrace, all danger ceases. Such is the child's reliance upon the parent—how could one wish to leave that embrace, even for a moment? Yet parents desire their children's success, so they sever their affection and entrust them to outside teachers. Children wish to gain renown and honor their parents, so they follow their teachers to distant lands—to the lands of Qi and Lu, even to Chu and Yue, without hesitation. Parents and children exchange hopes and expectations, where no deception can hide. Yet fate grants some swift fortune and others slow, some meet success while others meet hardship. One may rise to prominence only to find parents already gone; parents may live long yet poverty prevents proper ceremony. Thus among a thousand, perhaps one or two achieve both the child's success and the parent's wished-for joy while both still live. To fulfill the rites of honoring one's parents in such a time—this is to face heaven and earth without shame, and to content one's heart fully.

    My friend Cao Daxu passed the examinations in the year of the Rat and entered the Hanlin Academy, where his mastery of classical learning earned him selection to the Hongmun Academy. There he served the king closely and received exceptional royal favor. All expected him to become a minister. In the spring of the year of the Pig, following the rites, he requested permission to hold a filial piety ceremony in Geumsan County of Gyeongsang Province. Both his parents yet lived in good health, making his honor complete. As he was about to depart, he came to me asking for words to accompany him. I said: "Cao Daxu, how fortunate you are!"

    "Daxu will leave the palace and travel southward. As he approaches his home and gazes upon it, the mulberry trees stand thick and green. Entering the village gates, friends gather to observe his arrival; servants greet him with joy. He opens the doors, bows in the courtyard, and lifting his gaze sees both parents' faces on the platform, breaking into radiant smiles. Drawing back, he exchanges greetings with his siblings. Wine and food are laid out; laughter and conversation bloom, warmth filling every room. Soon the local officials arrange a grand banquet. The tables overflow with delicacies, land and water offerings arranged in splendor. Songs of the South echo, the music of White Flowers plays. Joy suffuses everything. In brilliant robes, people dance as celebration reaches its peak. Looking up, he sees the golden light of contentment illuminating his parents' brows. In this moment, he fulfills his deepest longing and repays his parents' wishes a thousandfold. Cao Daxu, how fortunate you are!"

    I myself received instruction in filial piety from my youth. Though my accomplishments have been limited, I passed the jinshi examination at sixteen and, undeservedly, topped the civil service examination at twenty-four. At that time my parents had not yet reached sixty. I wished to hold a filial piety ceremony according to the law, but my father, the late Minister Dae Mun-gong, by nature disliked ostentation. He refused again and again. I pressed him earnestly, but he taught me: "Where there is honor, disgrace follows. Honor and disgrace bring fortune and misfortune. How could I abandon my nature to accept your honor?" He refused firmly. Yet I thought to myself: "Though I cannot provide one complete day of joy, if my parents live long, will there not be many opportunities to honor them?" This consoled me.

    At thirty-five I rose to high office, and my parents rejoiced greatly. I too felt blessed to have brought honor to them. That very winter, my mother passed away. The following autumn, my father joined her. Two graves rose upon a hillside, and all my hopes of honoring them crumbled into dust with nowhere to rest.

    For more than twenty years after, I received excessive grace from the throne, serving in the six ministries. My salary was sufficient to support my parents, yet there was no one to support. My position could have brought them honor, yet I could not honor them. When the five-year cycle granted me leave to visit their graves, I would find the trees obscuring their resting place. Bowing at the spirit path, old grass covered their mounds while poplars wailed in the wind. Pouring wine before the stones, my tears flowed without ceasing. There was no voice to hear, no face to see. Remembering parents lost in time carelessly squandered, how could I not bear shame in my heart and sorrow until death?

    Now, even if I gave all my rank and salary, could I purchase half a day of Daxu's joy? Whether Daxu will ultimately achieve the fullness of filial honor that surpasses my own—this cannot be foretold. Yet his path lies long ahead. Having fulfilled the rites from beginning to end, the day of providing five-fold feasts and three precious offerings approaches swiftly. How unlike my own path, where nothing remains but regret.

    In ancient times, Kou Zhun, in his youth, loved hunting and falconry. His mother, stern by nature, threw a scale weight at him, striking his foot until it bled. From that day, he turned to study. But when he rose to prominence and became an official, his mother had already passed. He would touch the scar and weep. When first appointed Director of the Bureau of Military Affairs, the rewards of gold and silk were considerable. His wet nurse wept, saying: "When the Lady lived, we could not find even one bolt of silk to make her burial clothes. How could we know such wealth would come?" He wailed and distributed all the gold and silk among the people, never accumulating wealth in his remaining years.

    Alas, from ancient times to now, who does not wish to gain wealth and honor to support their parents? Yet should fortune come while parents are gone, what use is it? Therefore, I burden Daxu with these long words—truly, to hold Kou Zhun's sorrow as a mirror, to take my own regret as warning, to urge him to cherish each remaining day with utmost devotion, that he may harbor no regrets in time to come.

    Written respectfully in the early days of the sixth month.
  footnotes:
    - The 'five-fold feasts' (五鼎) and 'three precious offerings' (三牲) refer to elaborate ceremonial feasts traditionally offered to honor one's parents.
    - Kou Zhun (寇准, 961-1023) was a famous Song dynasty official. The anecdote about his mother's sternness and his later regret became a classic example in Confucian literature of filial piety and the dangers of delayed gratitude.
    - The 'Song of the South' (南陔) and 'White Flowers' (白華) are classical ritual songs used at ceremonial occasions.
